# 4. Service Account

Every namespace automatically contains a **default ServiceAccount**.

Every Pod automatically gets this ServiceAccount unless another one is specified.

Inside the container

```bash
cd /run/secrets/kubernetes.io/serviceaccount/
```

You'll find

```
token
ca.crt
namespace
```

Example

```
/run/secrets/kubernetes.io/serviceaccount/

├── token
├── ca.crt
└── namespace
```

---

# Purpose of These Files

### token

Authentication token used to communicate with Kubernetes API Server.

### ca.crt

Certificate Authority certificate used to verify the API Server.

### namespace

Current namespace in which the Pod is running.

---

# 5. Communicate with Kubernetes API Server

Store the token

```bash
token=$(cat /run/secrets/kubernetes.io/serviceaccount/token)
```

Call the API

```bash
curl -k \
-H "Authorization: Bearer $token" \
https://<API_SERVER_IP>:6443/api/v1
```

Find API Server

```bash
kubectl cluster-info
```

Example output

```
Kubernetes control plane is running at

https://172.30.1.2:6443
```

Why?

Applications running inside a Pod can securely communicate with the Kubernetes API Server.

Examples:

- Get Pods
- Create Pods
- Read ConfigMaps
- Read Secrets

