# 7. Projected Volume on Worker Node

Every Pod has a unique UID.

On the worker node

```text
/var/lib/kubelet/pods/<UID>/volumes/kubernetes.io~projected/
```

Example

```
/var/lib/kubelet/pods/
        │
        └── UID
              │
              └── volumes
                      │
                      └── kubernetes.io~projected
```
"When a Pod is created, Kubernetes automatically mounts the ServiceAccount credentials at /run/secrets/kubernetes.io/serviceaccount. 
This directory contains the ServiceAccount token, CA certificate, and namespace, which are used by applications inside the Pod to 
authenticate and communicate with the Kubernetes API Server. Since these credentials are sensitive, Kubernetes mounts this volume as read-only. 
That's why touch abc fails with a 'Read-only file system' error."

Shorter version (30-second interview answer)

"By default, when a Pod is created, Kubernetes mounts the ServiceAccount Secret at /run/secrets/kubernetes.io/serviceaccount. 
This contains the token and certificates used to communicate securely with the Kubernetes API Server. Since it's a Secret volume, 
Kubernetes mounts it as read-only for security, so we cannot create or modify files there."


