# 9. ConfigMap

A ConfigMap stores configuration data separately from the container image.

Instead of rebuilding the image, configuration can be mounted into the Pod.

Flow

```
Local File
     ↓
ConfigMap
     ↓
Pod
     ↓
Container
```

Create a file

```bash
echo "Hello Vaibhav" > /tmp/sanjay.txt
```

Create ConfigMap

```bash
kubectl create configmap my-config --from-file=/tmp/sanjay.txt
```

Verify

```bash
kubectl get configmaps
```

Describe

```bash
kubectl describe configmap my-config
```

---

# ConfigMap Pod YAML

```yaml
apiVersion: v1
kind: Pod

metadata:
  name: configmap-volume-demo

spec:
  containers:
  - name: app
    image: nginx

    volumeMounts:
    - name: foo
      mountPath: /etc/foo
      readOnly: true

  volumes:
  - name: foo
    configMap:
      name: my-config
```

Create Pod

```bash
kubectl apply -f pod.yaml
```

Enter Pod

```bash
kubectl exec -it configmap-volume-demo -- /bin/bash
```

Check mounted files

```bash
cd /etc/foo
ls
cat sanjay.txt
```

Expected Output

```
Hello Vaibhav
```

---

# ConfigMap Flow

```
Local File
      │
      ▼
kubectl create configmap
      │
      ▼
ConfigMap Stored in Kubernetes
      │
      ▼
Mounted into Pod
      │
      ▼
Container Reads Configuration
```

---

# Summary

| Volume Type | Purpose | Lifetime | Storage |
|-------------|---------|----------|---------|
| Projected Volume | ServiceAccount Token, ConfigMap, Secret, Downward API | Until Pod is deleted | Kubernetes Managed |
| EmptyDir | Temporary shared storage | Until Pod is deleted | Disk or RAM |
| ConfigMap | Configuration files | Until ConfigMap is deleted | Stored in etcd |

